{{Infobox academic | name = Gary Habermas | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Gary Robert Habermas | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|06|28}} | birth_place = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], US | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | residence = [[Lynchburg, Virginia|Lynchburg]], [[Virginia]], US | known_for = | spouse = {{unbulleted list | {{nowrap|Debbie ({{abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;{{circa|1972}}; {{abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1995)}} | Eileen}} | website = {{official URL}} | alma_mater = {{unbulleted list | [[William Tyndale College]] | [[University of Detroit]] | [[Michigan State University]]}} | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | school_tradition = [[Evangelicalism]] | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | influences = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | discipline = {{hlist | History | philosophy | theology}} | sub_discipline = <!--academic discipline specialist area – e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist--> | workplaces = [[Liberty University]] | doctoral_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | notable_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = [[Resurrection of Jesus]] | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influenced = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | signature = | signature_alt = }} '''Gary Robert Habermas''' (born 1950) is an American historian, New Testament scholar, [[philosopher of religion]], and Christian [[apologist]] who frequently writes and lectures on the [[resurrection of Jesus]].
==Life and career== Habermas is Distinguished Professor of Apologetics and Philosophy and chairman of the department of philosophy and theology at [[Liberty University]] in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=EPS Author Profile|url=http://www.epsociety.org/library/authors.asp?mode=profile&pid=16|publisher=Evangelical Philosophical Society}}</ref> He holds a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree (1976) from [[Michigan State University]] in history and [[philosophy of religion]] and a master's degree (1973) from the [[University of Detroit]] in [[philosophical theology]].<ref>http://www.liberty.edu/academics/religion/?PID=2246</ref> He has specialized in cataloging and communicating trends among scholars in the field of [[historical Jesus]] and [[New Testament]] studies.{{cn|date=May 2018}}
